<br>
This is a really interesting MMOG, and the philosophy is a lot different from EQ’s. It plays more like Diablo, with its movement controls and camera pans. You’re always in 3rd person view, and the angle depends on how you’ve got your mouse positioned on the edge of the screen. Think of the 4th and 5th F9 views with zoom control added. It takes a little getting used to.<br>
<br>
Like DAOC, Shadowbane lumps skills and spells into the same usage. As you gain levels, your new abilities pop up, and you get a choice of which to develop. You have to seek out a trainer and pay gold to develop these abilities. They don’t improve in game. There’s a little leeway in how you can develop your character, but at least this way it doesn’t make all clerics alike, etc. You can be really good at one thing, or pretty good at a lot of things. Plus, chances are, you’ll get abilities that deviate from the norm…for instance, I’m playing a priest, and I’ve got the ability to mez opponents. I will eventually be able to summon PCs, and then create pets. Not exactly EQ cleric here.<br>
<br>
Instead of a big collection of zones, each continent is one big zone. There’s no LOADING PLEASE WAIT. The only time you have to go through the waiting process is when your character gates to a different city. This process is also hugely different from EQ. Everyone is in the same boat in that they have to pledge (bind) at a city. Right now, the game mostly has NPC cities, but player-created cities are beginning to pop up. What makes it interesting is that each city, whether NPC or PC controlled, is considered a guild. If you wish to gate to another city, that involves quitting your guild and joining a new one. Not so big a deal when you’re errant (unguilded). But after joining an established player guild, then deciding you want to gate to another city, everyone in your guild will see that you left the guild when you used the gate! Interesting ramifications there, as if PC guilds didn’t have enough to fret about.<br>
<br>
Combat is much the same as in any MMOG. Gang up on monsters and kill them. The group management tools aren’t as exact as EQ’s. There’s no other to target group members than to mouse click on them, for instance. But the group leader gets some neat abilities. He can make the group march in formations, like columns, lines, circles, wedges, etc. Dogboy was making us all dizzy the other night doing this. This is cool because there’s less risk of members getting lost or left behind (unless they’re having lag issues. Yes, it happens here too. :-( ).<br>
<br>
After you reach 20th, you can PK or be PKed by anybody. However, there’s certain things in the game that makes you think twice about griefing other players. Your guild’s city is likely to be attacked by the victim’s guild. Certain casters will remember PKs and not summon/heal you etc. Moreover, the PK presence adds more desperation to the game. One time I was following the guild around looking for a rat rune camp, and they decided to pledge at a nearby city. We ran around forever looking for it, and by the time we got there, we saw smoking ruins where a building used to be. The Tree of Life (and Runemaster) were still there, but the only other building was an empty armory. We decided to adopt the place as our new hometown and pledged there. Eventually, I got killed and respawned there, and saw the original builders wandering around pissed off at what happened to their city. I just quietly repledged and gated out.<br>
<br>
When you die, you reform at pledge point with all your equipment, but your inventory (your loot and coin) is at your gravesite. Anybody can loot it before you get back. Therefore, I get my ass to a bank ASAP after an adventure session so I don’t lose my loot. Banks a few and far between in Shadowbane, so the desperation factor gets pretty damn high.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I play Klaproth on the Mourning server, so if anybody picks this game up, look me up. Talk atcha later.<br>
